# Engine Manifest

This file enumerates the loadable Selvedge engine at the current commit. The engine is the file set listed below plus the substrate; loading the engine means having these files available, the substrate initialised, and the `selvedge` CLI on PATH.

## Current engine version

`engine-v34` (established Session 118 — opens_issue effects now require target_issue_id at submit time, mirroring closes_issue at engine-v28).

`engine-v34` ships migration 022 adding T-31 (`t31_opens_issue_requires_target_issue`) which refuses any `decision_effects` INSERT with `effect_kind='opens_issue'` and NULL `target_issue_id`. The `_submit_decision_record` handler's opens_issue branch resolves `target` (issue alias) via `_resolve_issue_alias` and refuses unless the resolved issue has `status='open'`; this protects against opens_issue effects citing already-resolved or superseded issues, a logical-consistency check absent from the closes_issue side because closes_issue dispatches the disposition transition itself. Unlike closes_issue, opens_issue does not dispatch issue creation in-band — operators register issues separately via `submit issue` and reference them from the decision-record. Rationale per DV-S118-1 R-1.1 rejection: folding title/priority/summary/body into decision_effects payload bloats the schema for marginal ergonomic gain. Eight legacy NULL `target_issue_id` rows pre-date T-31 and remain untouched (T-31 is BEFORE INSERT only); the chain-walk export (`_decisions_citing_issue` in cli.py ~L2806) retains its target_descriptor word-boundary regex fallback to traverse them. Closes EF-S117-1 (S117 friction observation: 8/14 opens_issue rows carried NULL target_issue_id, forcing descriptor-substring fallback in DV-S116-1 anchor-trace). prompt-development v7 documents the new authoring contract.

`engine-v33` (established Session 110 — substrate-direct read for `monitor-external harvest-ef`; ledger-based per-row idempotency).

`engine-v33` ships migration 019 (`harvested_engine_feedback` ledger with UNIQUE(peer_workspace_id, peer_feedback_id), FK to objects + sessions) plus a rewrite of `_me_harvest_ef` and `_me_status` to read peer `engine_feedback` rows directly from the peer SQLite via read-only URI with `PRAGMA busy_timeout=1000` and `PRAGMA query_only=1`. The previous file-walk path is removed; against substrate-only peers (the live disaster-recovery workspace was the trigger) it returned silently-empty. Per S110 D-1 deliberation_id=10 (P-1 anthropic, P-2 codex/openai cross-family) the design adopted: capability-based peer schema detection (objects.alias vs older citable_alias detected via `pragma_table_info`) over migration-version gating; per-row dedup via the ledger over `--since-session` as the dedup mechanism (`--since-session` retained as optional coarse filter); SQLite native busy_timeout over Python retry-with-backoff. Four new structured error codes: E_PEER_BUSY, E_PEER_OPEN_FAILED, E_PEER_QUERY_FAILED, E_PEER_SCHEMA_UNSUPPORTED. Reviewer caught the EF-S005-7 vs EF-S005-1 alias precision error (peer feedback_id=7 has alias EF-S005-1 because aliases are per-session ordinals, not absolute feedback_ids). Three iterations: iter-1 surfaced 2 high + 4 medium (OperationalError ambiguity, docstring, race-window UNIQUE labelling, empty-rows note, role closure capture); iter-2 surfaced 2 medium (schema-validation queries unwrapped, docstring Raises incomplete) addressed via _peer_exec inner helper; iter-3 clean.

`engine-v32` (established Session 109 — subtracts `specifications/constraints.md` from the engine-definition file set). The document carried historical design rationale (six properties of LLM agents learned over 75 sessions) with no operational content for external-problem agents. Every constraint it named is already encoded structurally in the substrate triggers and the methodology kernel; the rationale is permanently queryable via `bin/selvedge query` on the decisions substrate. Archive copy at `archive/specifications/constraints-v1.md`. Also backfills the substrate table enumeration through migration 018, closing FR-S107-11/FR-S108-10, and corrects frontmatter version drift carried since engine-v31 shipped without updating the file-body version number.

`engine-v31` (established Session 104 — substrate enforcement of the coding review loop, closing OI-083-001).

`engine-v31` ships migrations 017 + 018 plus a new substrate-only submit kind. Migration 017 adds `sessions.kind` (operator-declared at open: coding/spec_only/meta; immutable post-open via T-29 mirroring T-23 slug pattern) and the `review_passes` table (one row per reviewer iteration; outcome ∈ clean/findings/nonconverged with operator-asserted `head_sha` for staleness audit). T-30 refuses close on a coding session unless the latest review_pass is outcome=clean or outcome=nonconverged with halt_issue_id NOT NULL. T-20 narrowed to admit the halt path so unresolved findings can be recorded honestly. Migration 018 grants `__cli__` insert capability on `review_passes`. The new `submit review-pass` handler closes the structural-enforcement gap OI-083-001 named (S083 D-2 introduced the coding review loop in methodology v3 but left enforcement as operator-policed). P-2 (codex/openai) cross-family perspective surfaced the staleness-protection requirement (now embodied as `head_sha`) and the manifest-hash-sealing alternative recorded as forward direction OI-S104-1. Halted-as-status-value deferred to OI-S104-3 because admitting it would require a calibrated rebuild of the heavily-FK'd `sessions` table; halt is currently encoded by the review_pass row's outcome on a `status='closed'` session. Methodology v4 supersedes v3 with the substrate-now-enforces sentence.

`engine-v30` (established Session 102 — migration 016 renames `objects.citable_alias` → `objects.alias` and `issues.citable_alias` → `issues.alias` via `ALTER TABLE … RENAME COLUMN` (SQLite ≥ 3.25), with the T-22 alias-format trigger reissued so its RAISE message names the new column. The first migration attempt used the calibrated table-recreation dance and tripped FK-constraint-failed at COMMIT because dropping `objects` orphans dozens of referrers within the transaction; switching to RENAME COLUMN is non-destructive and auto-rewrites trigger-body column references (only string literals in RAISE need manual update). Closes OI-S101-1 (LOW): the column was the most-trafficked schema name and the rename removes the `o.citable_alias AS alias` indirection that several read-paths in `cli.py` had already adopted. CLI handlers and tests refactored hard-cut: payload field is now `alias`, not `citable_alias`.

`engine-v29` (established Session 099 — extends `_submit_spec_version` to accept inline `body_md`). The handler validates that `body_path` resolves under `workspace_root` (refusing `..`-traversal escapes via `Path.resolve(strict=False).relative_to(ws)`), computes the body_sha256 from the inline content (refusing on declared-vs-computed mismatch), encodes utf-8 bytes-for-bytes, and writes the file in-process *after* the spec_versions INSERT and the engine-manifest workspace_metadata UPDATE succeed (so a constraint refusal never leaves an orphaned body file). Closes OI-S090-5: spec body authoring is now part of the substrate write transaction, replacing the Bash heredoc bypass that S090–S098 relied on when the PreToolUse hook refused Edit/Write/MultiEdit/NotebookEdit on substrate-canonical markdown. `prompt-development` v4 documents the new authoring path in §6 and the `closes_issue` effect contract in §5.

`engine-v28` (established Session 098 — migration 014 closes_issue effect wiring: typed `decision_effects.target_issue_id` column with FK to `issues`; T-17 reissued to admit it; T-27 refuses `closes_issue` effects with NULL `target_issue_id`; T-28 refuses any direct `decision_effects` INSERT bypassing the handler-side dispatch). Migration 015 (calibrated table-recreation) widens the `decision_effects` UNIQUE to include `target_issue_id` so multiple closes_issue effects within one decision can coexist; triggers reissued outside the calibrated block per S098 EF-S098-2. The `_submit_decision_v2` handler now dispatches `closes_issue` effects through `_submit_issue_disposition` in the same `write_tx`. `bin/selvedge export --session` renders closes_issue effect lines as `kind alias — descriptor`.

`engine-v27` (established Session 097 — migration 013 `forward_reference_dispositions` table + T-26 facet gate, two new submit handlers `engine-feedback-disposition` and `forward-reference-disposition`, and `prompt-development` v3 adding §1.5 self-driving dispatch and §8.5 close-time reflection).

`engine-v26` (established Session 094 — adds the `submit engine-feedback` handler so authoring follows substrate-only-writes. Also fixes two `bin/selvedge export --issues` UX bugs: dry-run output now uses `files_planned` with a `dry_run: true` flag, and `--write` now reconciles open↔resolved transitions by deleting stale on-disk files).

`engine-v25` (established Session 091 — migration 011 plus a one-line addition to `_submit_spec_version`: when `spec_id='engine-manifest'`, the handler atomically updates `workspace_metadata.current_engine_version` inside the same write transaction. Migration 011 backfills the metadata to engine-v24 and seeds the `__cli__` UPDATE capability. Also resolves OI-086-002 as already-satisfied).

`engine-v24` (established Session 090 — ships the PreToolUse hook (`tools/hooks/refuse-substrate-md.py`) wired in `.claude/settings.json` that refuses Edit/Write/MultiEdit/NotebookEdit on `provenance/**/*.md`, `specifications/*.md`, `prompts/*.md`, and `open-issues/**/*.md` unless `SELVEDGE_EXPORT_CONTEXT=1` is set. Resolves OI-085-002 (HIGH): markdown is now structurally non-authoritative for substrate-canonical surfaces).

`engine-v23` (established Session 089 — substrate-native dispatch tooling: `selvedge orient` aggregator CLI; `selvedge schema` introspection CLI; `selvedge export --issues` materialiser; issue↔work_item M:N linkage with T-24 orphan-on-resolve refusal).

`engine-v23` ships migration 010 (`state/migrations/010-issue-work-items.sql`) plus three new CLI subcommands (`selvedge orient`, `selvedge schema`, `selvedge export --issues`). Migration 010 adds the `issue_work_items` join table (M:N: a single work_item may resolve multiple issues — the realistic case is one fix closing several tracked issues at once), widens `work_items.kind` to admit `issue_resolution` (the existing session-phase taxonomy preserved as superset), and adds T-24: refuses an issue's status moving to `resolved`/`superseded` while any linked work_item with relation `resolves` is still `queued` or `leased`. `selvedge orient` prints a single live-read packet (workspace metadata, recent close-records, forward references from `next_session_should`, open issues capped at 30, in-flight work_items, active specs, deferred decisions, open review findings); markdown by default with `--json` flag, never materialised to disk. `selvedge schema` introspects `sqlite_master` and emits a formatted table-by-table summary with parsed CHECK enums (or `--raw` DDL). `selvedge export --issues` materialises `open-issues/<alias>.md` from substrate so issue files stay git-trackable even though the substrate is canonical. PROMPT.md and prompts/development.md updated to point at `bin/selvedge orient` as the first session step. Per S089 D-1, design followed three-perspective deliberation (P-1 anthropic-pragmatic, P-2 codex-cross-family, P-3 anthropic-adversarial); synthesis adopted M:N join over single-column linkage, markdown-default over JSON-default, derived state via LEFT JOIN over explicit decomposition_status column, minimal kind-enum widening, T-24 only (deferred T-25 lease-renewal trigger).

`engine-v22` (established Session 088 — issues substrate table replaces 25 markdown OIs as the canonical dispatch surface).

`engine-v22` ships migration 009 (`state/migrations/009-issues-table.sql`) plus four new CLI submit kinds (`submit issue`, `submit issue-disposition`, `submit issue-link`, `submit issue-note`). Tables: `issues` (per-issue row with `citable_alias`, `surfaced_session_id`, `title_atom_id`, optional `summary_atom_id`/`body_atom_id`, closed-enum `priority` HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW, closed-enum `status` open/in_progress/blocked/resolved/superseded), `issue_links` (directed edges with relation enum blocks/supersedes/duplicates/folds_into/related), `issue_notes` (append-only annotations), `issue_dispositions` (state-transition rows that are the only way `status` moves). Triggers: T-22 (alias-format GLOB), T-22a (terminal-status requires resolved_session_id+resolved_at), T-23 (no self-loops on issue_links). Issues do NOT register in the `objects` table — alias resolution lives on `issues.alias` (renamed from `citable_alias` at engine-v30) directly, sidestepping the FK-cascade pain of recreating `objects`. Future cross-citation can ship via a separate widening migration if needed. The 25 pre-existing markdown OIs were backfilled by a session 088 subagent; their compressed canonical bodies are in substrate, their verbatim prose is in git history. Per S088 D-1, schema design followed three-perspective deliberation (anthropic-pragmatic, codex-cross-family, anthropic-adversarial) with synthesis preserving dissent.

`engine-v21` (established Session 087 — migration 008 widens T-06 to admit `body_canonical_in_substrate` flips on closed-session spec_version rows, unblocking cross-session decomposition completion).

`engine-v21` ships migration 008 (`state/migrations/008-widen-t06-for-canonical-flag.sql`). The original T-06 trigger on `spec_versions` UPDATE refused all non-status mutations of closed-session rows. Decomposition completion (`body_canonical_in_substrate` 0 → 1) is a per-session activity that legitimately spans sessions: a row's creation session may register a pointer-only spec_version, and a later session may complete the substrate decomposition. The widened trigger admits flag transitions in both directions while continuing to refuse content edits (`body_path`, `body_sha256`, etc.) on closed-session rows. The migration also performs a one-time backfill, flipping the flag to 1 on the three v2 rows whose decomposition completed in session 087: `engine-manifest v20`, `prompt-application v2`, `prompt-development v2`.

`engine-v20` (established Session 084 — Path A substrate-only write path per operator direction).

`engine-v20` ships a structural reorientation: the SQLite substrate becomes the only writable surface for session state and specifications; markdown files in `provenance/` and `specifications/` become *exports* generated by `bin/selvedge export --session <N> --write`. Per the deliberation in S084 (deliberation_id=3, three perspectives P-1/P-2/P-3 with synthesis preserving dissent), the operator ratified Path A (P-1 strictest): the substrate refuses prose-in-rows by construction. New tables (`text_atoms`, `decisions_v2`, `decision_supports`, `decision_effects`, `alternatives_v2`, `alternative_rejections`, `spec_sections`, `spec_clauses`, `spec_clause_links`, `assessments`, `assessment_agenda_items`, `perspective_positions`, `perspective_claims`, `review_findings`, `close_records`, `close_state_items`, `legacy_imports`) hold typed atoms (length-bounded, newline-free, no fenced code, no pipe tables) and typed link rows with closed-enum bases. Migrations 003 (Path A schema) and 004 (CR-guard trigger T-21) ship together.

The 078 D-5 release gate's "no methodology-expanding self-development sessions modify active spec content" clause is overridden by operator directive (recorded at S084 D-2 / substrate D-S005-2 R-1.3, with the reason). Per `specifications/methodology.md` §When to convene multiple agents, the no-cross-family-deliberation exception was not invoked: a three-perspective deliberation including a cross-family P-1 (codex/OpenAI) was convened and is recorded at deliberation_id=3.

T-15 was operator-calibrated at S084 D-1: a `-- T-15-CALIBRATED-BEGIN: <reason>` / `-- T-15-CALIBRATED-END` marker pair admits non-destructive CHECK-relaxation table-recreation (validated by the runner: only CREATE TABLE / INSERT INTO ... SELECT / DROP TABLE / ALTER TABLE ... RENAME / CREATE INDEX / CREATE TRIGGER admitted inside the block). The runner refuses other DDL inside the markers.

`engine-v20` remains **provisional** in the same sense `engine-v19` was: no further methodology-expanding self-development sessions modify active spec content between 084 and the close of the first external-problem trial of 30 sessions, except where operator-directed.

`engine-v19` adds a structural reviewer mechanism for code-producing sessions: a reviewer subagent, distinct from the implementer, audits any change to executable code (Python under `selvedge/`, SQL under `state/migrations/`, shell under `bin/` or `tools/`), and the loop continues until the reviewer reports no medium-or-higher findings remain. The pre-existing engine-definition close review is retained as a single-pass mechanism. Both are documented in `specifications/methodology.md` §When to review and wired into `prompts/development.md` and `prompts/application.md`.

The change is operator-directed and is recorded as a deliberate exception to the 078 D-5 release gate. Specifically, the gate's clause forbidding methodology-expanding self-development sessions from modifying active spec content between Session 079 and the close of the first external-problem trial of 30 sessions is overridden for this revision by operator directive (recorded in S083 D-2 / substrate D-S004-2 R-1.3, with the reason). Per `specifications/methodology.md` §When to convene multiple agents (when multi-agent deliberation is otherwise triggered but not performed because the decision is operator-directed, the reason is recorded), no cross-family deliberation was convened on the loop's design details; the procedural exception itself is recorded at S083 D-1 / substrate D-S004-1, and a future cross-family review of the loop's design details is deferred until the mechanism has been exercised against real code-producing sessions.

`engine-v19` remains **provisional** in the same sense `engine-v18` was: no further methodology-expanding self-development sessions modify active spec content between 083 and the close of the first external-problem trial of 30 sessions, except where operator-directed. Bug-fix and validator-tightening sessions remain admitted.

