../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:14:## Current engine version
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:22:`engine-v33` ships migration 019 (`harvested_engine_feedback` ledger with UNIQUE(peer_workspace_id, peer_feedback_id), FK to objects + sessions) plus a rewrite of `_me_harvest_ef` and `_me_status` to read peer `engine_feedback` rows directly from the peer SQLite via read-only URI with `PRAGMA busy_timeout=1000` and `PRAGMA query_only=1`. The previous file-walk path is removed; against substrate-only peers (the live disaster-recovery workspace was the trigger) it returned silently-empty. Per S110 D-1 deliberation_id=10 (P-1 anthropic, P-2 codex/openai cross-family) the design adopted: capability-based peer schema detection (objects.alias vs older citable_alias detected via `pragma_table_info`) over migration-version gating; per-row dedup via the ledger over `--since-session` as the dedup mechanism (`--since-session` retained as optional coarse filter); SQLite native busy_timeout over Python retry-with-backoff. Four new structured error codes: E_PEER_BUSY, E_PEER_OPEN_FAILED, E_PEER_QUERY_FAILED, E_PEER_SCHEMA_UNSUPPORTED. Reviewer caught the EF-S005-7 vs EF-S005-1 alias precision error (peer feedback_id=7 has alias EF-S005-1 because aliases are per-session ordinals, not absolute feedback_ids). Three iterations: iter-1 surfaced 2 high + 4 medium (OperationalError ambiguity, docstring, race-window UNIQUE labelling, empty-rows note, role closure capture); iter-2 surfaced 2 medium (schema-validation queries unwrapped, docstring Raises incomplete) addressed via _peer_exec inner helper; iter-3 clean.
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:24:`engine-v32` (established Session 109 — subtracts `specifications/constraints.md` from the engine-definition file set). The document carried historical design rationale (six properties of LLM agents learned over 75 sessions) with no operational content for external-problem agents. Every constraint it named is already encoded structurally in the substrate triggers and the methodology kernel; the rationale is permanently queryable via `bin/selvedge query` on the decisions substrate. Archive copy at `archive/specifications/constraints-v1.md`. Also backfills the substrate table enumeration through migration 018, closing FR-S107-11/FR-S108-10, and corrects frontmatter version drift carried since engine-v31 shipped without updating the file-body version number.
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:32:`engine-v29` (established Session 099 — extends `_submit_spec_version` to accept inline `body_md`). The handler validates that `body_path` resolves under `workspace_root` (refusing `..`-traversal escapes via `Path.resolve(strict=False).relative_to(ws)`), computes the body_sha256 from the inline content (refusing on declared-vs-computed mismatch), encodes utf-8 bytes-for-bytes, and writes the file in-process *after* the spec_versions INSERT and the engine-manifest workspace_metadata UPDATE succeed (so a constraint refusal never leaves an orphaned body file). Closes OI-S090-5: spec body authoring is now part of the substrate write transaction, replacing the Bash heredoc bypass that S090–S098 relied on when the PreToolUse hook refused Edit/Write/MultiEdit/NotebookEdit on substrate-canonical markdown. `prompt-development` v4 documents the new authoring path in §6 and the `closes_issue` effect contract in §5.
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:40:`engine-v25` (established Session 091 — migration 011 plus a one-line addition to `_submit_spec_version`: when `spec_id='engine-manifest'`, the handler atomically updates `workspace_metadata.current_engine_version` inside the same write transaction. Migration 011 backfills the metadata to engine-v24 and seeds the `__cli__` UPDATE capability. Also resolves OI-086-002 as already-satisfied).
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:52:`engine-v21` (established Session 087 — migration 008 widens T-06 to admit `body_canonical_in_substrate` flips on closed-session spec_version rows, unblocking cross-session decomposition completion).
../../specifications/engine-manifest.md:54:`engine-v21` ships migration 008 (`state/migrations/008-widen-t06-for-canonical-flag.sql`). The original T-06 trigger on `spec_versions` UPDATE refused all non-status mutations of closed-session rows. Decomposition completion (`body_canonical_in_substrate` 0 → 1) is a per-session activity that legitimately spans sessions: a row's creation session may register a pointer-only spec_version, and a later session may complete the substrate decomposition. The widened trigger admits flag transitions in both directions while continuing to refuse content edits (`body_path`, `body_sha256`, etc.) on closed-session rows. The migration also performs a one-time backfill, flipping the flag to 1 on the three v2 rows whose decomposition completed in session 087: `engine-manifest v20`, `prompt-application v2`, `prompt-development v2`.
